Basic ggplot call

Plot gdpPercap vs lifeExp.

Basic components of ggplots:

  1. ggplot(),

  2. layers: geom_point, geom_line, geom_boxplot, geom_hex, … more geometric objects, known as geoms.

  3. add layers: +

library(ggplot2)

# draw on a whiteboard
ggplot()

# add a layer: points
#  1) data
#  2) variables (aes)
#  3) color, size, shape, fill

ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = gapminder, aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap))

Aesthetics: locally vs globally:

Dots with gdpPercap above 60000 are highlighted

ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = gapminder, 
             aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap)) +
  geom_point(data = gapminder %>%
               filter(gdpPercap >60000), 
             aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap), color = "red")

The data, x, y used in two layers are the same, so we could define them globally to simplify the code.

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_point(data = . %>%
               filter(gdpPercap >60000), color = "red")

Let’s change the colors, size, shape and the transparency of the points:

ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = gapminder, 
             aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap),
             color = "blue", size = 8, shape = 18, alpha = 0.2)

Let’s color the points by the continent

#Use default colors
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = gapminder, 
             aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = continent))

#Use custom colors
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = gapminder, 
             aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = continent)) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("orange", "blue", "green", "red", "pink"))

There are other scale_ options to change the shape, size, linetype, etc. Go to this link for ways to implement them.

Here we change the shape for each continent:

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data = gapminder,
             aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = continent, shape = continent)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("orange", "blue", "green", "red", "pink")) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = 1:5)

If we have a continuous variable like year, we should use a continuous gradient of colors and here, we’ve also modified the scale of the y axis to spread out the points more:

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data = gapminder, 
             aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = year)) +
  scale_y_sqrt()

We can change the color gradient by using for example, the rainbow palette rainbow():

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = year)) + 
  geom_point() +
  scale_color_gradientn(colours = rainbow(5))

  #We can also pick colours individually
  #scale_color_gradientn(colours = c("orange", "blue", "green", "red", "pink"))

We use the colorRampPalette function to generate a continuous gradient from any set of colors

library(RColorBrewer)

colors2 <- colorRampPalette(c("red", 'orange', "green", 'darkgreen'))(10)
colors2 #is a vector with all the color names

ggplot(data = gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = year)) +
  scale_colour_gradientn(colours = colors2)

The viridis package offers continuous color gradients designed in a way to ensure readability for readers with common forms of color vision deficiency. The package comes with convenience functions that can be directly used with the ggplot syntax. The different scales can be found here.

library(viridis)

ggplot(data = gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = year)) +
  scale_color_viridis_b()

Also commonly used is the brewer.pal function to choose a predefined set of colors. The RColorBrewer package offers both discrete and continuous color palettes. Take a look at them here

colors2 <- colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(n = 9, name = "YlGnBu"))(20)

ggplot(data = gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = year)) +
  scale_colour_gradientn(colours = colors2)


# or use scale_colour_distiller
ggplot(data = gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = year)) +
  scale_colour_distiller(palette = "YlGnBu", direction = 1)

More gradient scales: http://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/scale_gradient.html

Axis

The first two approaches (scale_x_continuous(limits = c()), xlim()) remove the data points before plotting.

ggplot(data = gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = continent)) +
  xlim(40, 70) 
## Warning: Removed 617 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# scale_x_continuous(limits = c(40, 70))  
# coord_cartesian(xlim = c(40, 70))
ggplot(data = gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = continent)) +
  scale_y_log10()

Theme

The black and white theme theme_bw():

ggplot(data = gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = continent)) +
  theme_bw()

Modify components of a theme see more here. See also the hrbrthemes package for additional themes.

ggplot(data = gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = continent)) +
  labs(x = "live", y = "GDP", title = "XXX") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"), 
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 15, hjust = 0.5))

Faceting

Let’s stratify the plot by continent with facet_wrap():

ggplot(data = gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x = lifeExp, y = gdpPercap, color = continent)) +
  facet_wrap(~ continent, nrow =1)

See also facet_grid() here

Other geoms

See http://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/

Histogram

Rather for continuous data.

Histogram of lifeExp:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = lifeExp)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1)

Colored by continent:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = lifeExp, fill = continent)) + #use fill instead of color
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1)

Density

Distribution of lifeExp represented with density:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = lifeExp, color = continent)) +
  geom_density()

Plot a line per country and color by continent:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = lifeExp, color = continent, group = country)) +
  geom_density()

Barplot

Rather for discrete data.

Count how many countries there are per continent:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = continent)) +
  geom_bar()

Violin plot + boxplot + jitter

We can plot multiple layers in one figure.

Let’s represent the distributions of gdpPercap for each continent:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = continent, y = gdpPercap, color = continent)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 0.5, alpha = 0.5) +
  #geom_boxplot(outlier.color = NA) +
  geom_violin(scale = "width")

Saving figures

Using pdf(), png(), bmp(), tiff(), or jpeg() and dev.off():

pdf("hist1.pdf")
ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 50) 
dev.off()

Using ggsave():

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 50) 

ggsave("hist3.pdf")
#ggsave("hist3.png")

Note that you can change the extension file in ggsave for any other image format (e.g. jpg, png, tiff), just by changing the file name.

Multipanel figures with cowplot

See Introduction to cowplot.

library(cowplot)

ggp1 <- ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 50)

ggp2 <- ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap)) +
  geom_density()

plot_grid(ggp1, ggp2, labels = c("A", "B"))

As an alternative the ggarrange function of the ggpubr package also provides an interface for multipanel figures and shared legends (ggpubr is actually a wrapper around cowplot).

library(ggpubr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'ggpubr'
## The following object is masked from 'package:cowplot':
## 
##     get_legend
ggp1 <- ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap, color=continent)) +
  scale_x_continuous(guide=guide_axis(n.dodge=3)) + # dodge can be used to avoid overlapping axis text
  geom_histogram(bins = 50)

ggp2 <- ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap, fill=continent)) +
  scale_x_continuous(guide=guide_axis(n.dodge=3)) + 
  geom_density()

ggarrange(ggp1, ggp2, ncol=2, common.legend = TRUE, legend="right")

2) Heatmap

library(ComplexHeatmap)

Colors & names

Let’s start by visualizing a simple matrix that contains 20 x 10 values drawn from a uniform distribution:

n_rows <- 20
n_cols <- 10
mat <- matrix(
  runif(n_rows * n_cols),
  nrow = n_rows, ncol = n_cols)
Heatmap(mat)

We can change the legend’s title using name:

Heatmap(mat, name = "counts")

And the color palette (default blue, white, red) using col:

Heatmap(mat, 
  name = "counts",
  col = c("white", "black"))

Each entry value can be visualized separately as a rectangular grid:

Heatmap(mat,
  name = "counts", 
  col = c("white", "black"),
  rect_gp = gpar(col = "white"))

Let’s add row and column labels by specifying the row and column names of the matrix:

rownames(mat) <- paste0("gene", 1:nrow(mat))
colnames(mat) <- paste0("sample", 1:ncol(mat))
Heatmap(mat)

Clustering & Labels

By default, Heatmap will re-order rows and columns according to hierarchical clustering, and add the corresponding dendrograms on the left and top. We can surpress this behavior by setting cluster_rows/columns = FALSE:

Heatmap(mat, 
  cluster_rows = FALSE, 
  cluster_columns = FALSE)

Let’s move the row labels to the left by setting row_names_side = "left":

Heatmap(mat, 
  cluster_rows = FALSE, 
  cluster_columns = FALSE, 
  row_names_side = "left")

If we prefer to show genes with the same pattern together, we could cluster the rows by setting cluster_rows = TRUE (the default):

Heatmap(mat, 
  cluster_rows = TRUE, 
  cluster_columns = FALSE, 
  row_names_side = "left")

Annotation

We can label the samples by adding an annotation to the columns of the heatmap:

sampAnno <- rep(c("Control", "Treated"), each = 5)
names(sampAnno) <- colnames(mat)
sampAnno
##   sample1   sample2   sample3   sample4   sample5   sample6   sample7   sample8 
## "Control" "Control" "Control" "Control" "Control" "Treated" "Treated" "Treated" 
##   sample9  sample10 
## "Treated" "Treated"
ha1 <- HeatmapAnnotation(group = sampAnno)
Heatmap(mat, 
  cluster_rows = TRUE, 
  cluster_columns = FALSE, 
  row_names_side = "left",
  top_annotation = ha1)

The colors for "Control" and "Treated" samples in the annotation above are random, and will change each time we redraw the heatmap above. We can fix these to a specific pair of colors using col in HeatmapAnnotation:

ha2 <- HeatmapAnnotation(
  group = sampAnno, 
  col = list(group = c(
    "Treated" = "orange", 
    "Control" = "grey")))
Heatmap(mat, 
  cluster_rows = TRUE, 
  cluster_columns = FALSE, 
  row_names_side = "left",
  top_annotation = ha2)

A boxplot on the right-hand side of the heatmap can be used to summarize the expression level of each gene across samplese:

ha3 <- rowAnnotation(expLevel = anno_boxplot(mat))
Heatmap(mat, 
  cluster_rows = TRUE, 
  cluster_columns = FALSE, 
  row_names_side = "left",
  top_annotation = ha2, 
  right_annotation = ha3)

We might want to compare the expression level of genes between groups. To do this, we draw a scatter plot. The groups are again highlighted in different colors.

ha4 <- rowAnnotation(value = anno_points(mat, 
  gp = gpar(col = rep(c("grey", "orange"), each = 5))))
Heatmap(mat, 
  cluster_rows = TRUE, 
  cluster_columns = FALSE, 
  row_names_side = "left",
  top_annotation = ha2, 
  right_annotation = ha4)

Legend & Titles

A legend for the scatter plot created above could be added as follows:

l = Legend(
  title = "value", type = "points",
  labels = c("Control", "Treated"), 
  legend_gp = gpar(
    col = c("grey", "orange"),
    fill = c("grey", "orange")))
p <- Heatmap(mat, 
  cluster_rows = TRUE, 
  cluster_columns = FALSE, 
  row_names_side = "left", 
  column_title = "Samples",
  top_annotation = ha2, 
  right_annotation = ha4)
draw(p, heatmap_legend_list = list(l))

Multiple heatmaps

The ComplexHeatmap package allows us to compute multiple Heatmaps using +:

p + p
